    "overall_strategy": "The synthesis network is grounded in the sole demonstrated prebiotic route to histidine from Shen et al. (1987, 1990), featuring erythrose and formamidine forming imidazole-4-acetaldehyde via Amadori rearrangement, followed by Strecker synthesis with HCN and NH3. Given the literature's emphasis on this pathway's challenges (e.g., formamidine instability, erythrose scarcity; V\u00e1zquez-Salazar et al., 2018), the network incorporates multiple convergent routes to precursors like erythrose (via stepwise aldol condensation and direct formose) and basic feedstocks (e.g., aldehydes from hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch feeding surface reactions). Alternative imidazole formations (Debus-Radziszewski, HCN photochemistry, Sutherland cascade) are included as potential extensions, though their direct link to histidine remains speculative and unverified, addressing the imidazole-4-acetaldehyde bottleneck. Environmental flow: Hydrothermal provides reducing H2/CO for aldehydes, Surface drives condensations/UV reactions with mineral stabilization, Biochemical enables final Strecker in concentrated pools. This creates redundancy with 10 pathways varying precursor sourcing, acknowledging open challenges like chirality and thermal instability.",
